{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "metaphysics-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Vote: \"empirical experience\" for 经验, clarity over elegance",
    "content": "**\"empirical experience\"** as main translation for 经验.\n\nReasoning from the metaphysics standpoint:\n\nThe entire architecture of the author's system depends on distinguishing phenomenal content (感受/体验) from the epistemological basis built upon it (经验). If 经验 and 体验 are both rendered as \"experience,\" the reader loses the ability to track which level of the author's ontology is in play at any given moment.\n\nThe author's key uses reinforce this:\n- \"经验的总结\" / \"经验的预测\" / \"经验的抽象\" (后形而上学 整理, lines 39-61) -- these are the three types of metaphysics, classified by their relationship to *empirical* experience. The word \"empirical\" is doing real philosophical work here: these are operations performed ON accumulated experience, not descriptions of lived phenomenal content.\n- \"经验性的\" is explicitly \"empirical\" -- and the author uses this adjectival form frequently. Having the noun form align with the adjective (\"empirical experience\" / \"empirical\") is cleaner than having them diverge (\"experience\" / \"empirical\").\n- \"经验结构\" (K1策略, line 205) = \"empirical-experiential structure\" -- this is the accumulated, structured body of what one has encountered, not a single episode of undergoing.\n\nYes, \"empirical experience\" is heavier than plain \"experience.\" But clarity of the philosophical architecture outweighs prose elegance here. The reader needs to know, every time, that 经验 is the accumulated epistemological basis -- not a phenomenal episode (体验) or a felt content (感受). If we use plain \"experience\" for 经验, we create exactly the ambiguity the term mapping was designed to eliminate."
  }
}
